INSERT INTO `cabinet` VALUES (1,'Velvet Falernum','Falernum is a syrup made in the Caribbean that is used in the place of simple syrup to complement and accentuate the flavour of rum. It is used in a few rum cocktails and is a nice addition, though can be very safely substituted as it’s quite uncommon.','Simple Syrup'),(2,'Triple Sec','Triple Sec is a very common orange liqueur. It has a sweet flavour and is made from macerating orange skins. Some recipes may call for Cointreau or Dry Curacao, but generic triple sec is totally fine.','Cointreau, Dry Curacao'),(3,'Sweet Vermouth','Sweet Vermouth is a fortified wine that is usually red in colour. It is used in a couple of cocktails.',NULL),(4,'Simple Syrup','Also known just as sugar syrup, simple is the most common syrup used in making cocktails. It can be bought or can be made by heating sugar and water in a saucepan at a ratio of 1:1 and stirring until it has dissolved.',NULL),(5,'Peach Schnapps','Peach Schnapps is a peach liqueur that is in a few cocktails like the Bermuda Cocktail. Even if you don’t use it much for mixing, it’s cheap(ish) and is nice with lemonade.',NULL),(6,'Passionfruit Liqueur','Often referred to by the brand, Passoa, passionfruit liqueur is pretty much only used to make Pornstar Martinis and nothing else.',NULL),(7,'Midori','Midori is a sweet melon liqueur from Japan. It tastes great but isn’t in too many recipes and isn’t very widely available.',NULL),(8,'Maraschino Liqueur','Maraschino Liqueur is a delicious cherry liqueur made from complex process involving crushing cherries and resting the alcohol in casks. It is used in a good few older recipes and I would suggest only buying it when you have a few recipes lined up because damn it is expensive.',NULL),(9,'Honey Syrup','Used in honey-themed recipes like The Bee’s Knees, it can be made by mixing honey and water at a 2:1 ratio respectively.',NULL),(10,'Grenadine','Grenadine is a very sweet pomegranate syrup. It is used to sweeten cocktails, like simple syrup does, but is most important in adding colour. Even a small amount can make cocktails go bright red, so make sure you don’t add too much so you get the perfect colour and sweetness.',NULL),(11,'Dry Vermouth','Dry Vermouth is a dry fortified wine. It is most known for it’s use in the classic Gin Martini so is worth buying if that is your thing.',NULL),(12,'Creme de Framboise','Often referred by the brand which has a monopoly on it, Chambord, raspberry liqueur is very sweet and is useful in some specific cocktails like the French Martini. It can usually be bought in small quantities so doesn’t need a lot of commitment.',NULL),(13,'Creme de Cassis','A blackcurrant liqueur used here and there in more classic cocktails like the Tequila Sunrise and the Russian Spring Punch.','Creme de Mure'),(14,'Coffee Liqueur','Coffee Liqueur isn’t used in a huge amount of recipes but still gets used up quite quickly because they are the type of recipes you want to make over and over again (like an Espresso Martini for example). As-well as tasting of coffee, it also adds sweetness. Patron and Kahlua are great brands, I would personally not get Tia Maria if the store has others.',NULL),(15,'Campari','Campari is a difficult aperitif to get used to because it is incredibly bitter. It has a complex taste of different fruits and is used in some famous cocktails like the Negroni but is not used very commonly.','Aperol'),(16,'Aperol','Aperol is a bitter aperitif featuring vibrant ingredients like rhubarb. It is most known for it’s use in the Aperol Spritz (which I haven’t made yet).','Campari (at your own risk)'),(17,'Angostura Bitters','Flavoured with many different herbs and spices like cloves and cinnamon, bitters are added to many cocktails to add complexity. Most recipes are fine without them, but their addition definitely brings the drink a step up. The brand does not need to be Angostura, though it’s by far the most popular.',NULL),(18,'Amaretto','Amaretto is a nutty almond liqueur. It’s probably one of the cheapest liqueurs available so is a good start for any back bar cabinet.',NULL),(19,'Agave Syrup','Sold in the baking isle of many supermarkets, agave syrup commonly replaces simple syrup in tequila recipes to complement the taste of tequila. It’s a good replacement but not absolutely essential.','Simple Syrup');
